    "descripcion_en": "The Plaza de la Afrocolombianidad is a civic public space created in 2001 to honor and make visible the fundamental contribution of black communities to the social, cultural and economic development of Santiago de Cali. Cali is home to the largest Afro-descendant population of a city in Colombia—more than 500,000 people—and this plaza is its symbol of recognition in the heart of the city. The space has commemorative plaques and busts of Afro-descendant leaders and intellectuals from southwestern Colombia, such as Benkos Biohó, Tránsito Chávez and Jorge Artel. During Afro-Colombian Week (May), the plaza is transformed into a vibrant setting for gastronomic displays of Pacific cuisine—arroz atollado, arroz con coco, encocado de camarón—, chonta and shawmía marimba auditions, and academic forums on the rights of black communities.",
